  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Designing Secure Chat Platform**\n\nI\'m currently focused on the core features: speed, simplicity, and encryption. My priority is finding the optimal balance for a seamless messaging experience. I\'m exploring different encryption methods to ensure it\'s secure yet easy to use. I need to keep the architecture simple to maintain the speed the user wants.\n\n\n**Clarifying User Requirements**\n\nI\'m now diving deeper into the user\'s intent to nail down the precise scope. The request is for a *very* simple, encrypted web chat platform for one-on-one communication. The focus is definitely on simplicity and speed. I\'m carefully considering the \"web olacak\" requirement. It seems real-time, multi-user is implied, but let\'s confirm the need for real-time capability given the \"simple\" constraint. I\'m focusing on a single screen structural layout.\n\n\n**Evaluating Technical Options**\n\nI\'m now weighing the technical aspects. Considering an Express + Vite app with WebSockets, or a server-authoritative REST/SSE approach, or even real-time Firebase Firestore. Given available skills, Firestore integration and real-time capabilities seem promising. The user\'s request for simple, password-protected, encrypted messages is key. End-to-end encryption using a shared secret seems perfect, with Firestore or a lightweight Express server for storage. Firestore\'s real-time listeners appear ideal for multi-user chat.\n\n\n**Assessing Firebase Integration**\n\nI\'m now grappling with Firebase\'s implications on the \"fast\" and \"simple\" requirements. The potential for out-of-the-box real-time functionality is appealing. However, the UI prompts for Firebase terms acceptance could impact the user\'s perception of speed and simplicity. It\'s a trade-off: speed and real-time versus a potentially clunkier initial setup process. I need to weigh if asking for confirmation will be too cumbersome for the user.\n\n\n**Exploring Express & SSE**\n\nI\'m now seriously considering an Express server with Server-Sent Events (SSE). It\'s incredibly appealing since it negates external dependencies. I can handle it directly inside the container on port 3000, eliminating any external database setup or UI prompts. The user experience should be extremely smooth and speedy with no setup. I\'m focusing on crafting a room-based message board where messages broadcast in real-time, all in memory!\n\n\n**Refining Encryption Methods**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on encryption. Considering the user\'s request for simplicity, AES-GCM or AES-CBC using the browser\'s SubtleCrypto API is ideal. It requires no npm packages and provides true end-to-end encryption. Alternatively, a password-derived key (PBKDF2 + AES-GCM) in the React frontend seems like a viable solution. It\'s a zero-knowledge approach: users enter a room name and shared password, with all encryption happening client-side. The server only sees encrypted ciphertext, a fantastic outcome!\n\n\n**Confirming Real-time Functionality**\n\nI\'ve just confirmed the multi-user aspect with SSE. The focus is on a real-time, zero-knowledge approach, leveraging client-side encryption. The SSE server ensures rapid, secure message broadcasts, and the password derivation secures everything. The key is to make it seamless.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 10
      nanos: 125618961
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
