    thinking: "**Considering App Design**\n\nI\'m now focusing on designing the architecture for `/src/App.tsx`. I need to break down the required modules and sections to maintain simplicity, as requested by the user. I\'m exploring the initial structure before jumping into the code. My goal is to map out the application\'s components.\n\n\n**Designing Chat Interface**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in the design of a user-friendly chat interface. I envision a sleek login screen that includes username and room ID inputs, and I want to add some fun features such as a random name generator and random room generation. It\'s imperative that the password key remains entirely client-side for maximum security. I am aiming to establish this login screen as a highly polished, secure access point.\n\n\n**Designing Chat Room Features**\n\nI\'m now detailing the Chat Room Screen, imagining a lock icon beside the room name, which will show the room ID. I\'m prioritizing user actions like resetting the room via `/api/rooms/:roomId/clear` and leaving it, both of which fit the privacy-focused theme. I am very enthusiastic about a feature to show the password key, and I\'m developing the idea to generate a shared link like `?room=xyz&key=abc` for friends, for a much friendlier experience! I\'m now exploring how to best implement URL query parameter parsing.\n\n\n**Developing Message Rendering**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the message display within the chat room. I\'m imagining a scrollable list with sender names (plus a \"Siz\" tag for the user), along with readable decrypted messages. I am aiming to incorporate a \"Show Encrypted Data\" toggle that, when activated, will reveal the ciphertext and IV in a visually striking cyberpunk terminal style. It\'s imperative that the timestamp formatting is clean and accurate.\n\nI\'m also building the message input box, which will trigger encryption and an API POST call with the encrypted data. I\'m planning to use the lucide-react send icon. Lastly, after sending, it must scroll to the bottom. I must write a robust SSE subscription system in React and keep an eye out for React 18+ double `useEffect` runs in dev.\n\n\n**Implementing SSE Connection**\n\nI\'m now writing the `useEffect` hook to manage the Server-Sent Events (SSE) connection. I\'m focusing on ensuring proper cleanup to prevent double `EventSource` instances, especially in React\'s StrictMode. I\'m aiming for a robust setup that handles message decryption and updates the chat feed efficiently. The plan involves parallel decryption of initial messages and real-time decryption of incoming messages.\n\n\n**Refining SSE Handler**\n\nI\'ve just fine-tuned the SSE hook. It now expertly prevents duplicate messages, automatically decrypts each incoming message using the `passwordKey`, and robustly handles SSE reconnection. The system also handles the messages received for the `/clear` endpoint. It is extremely clean and stable. I\'m very happy with how it\'s looking.\n\n\n**Defining Theme Styles**\n\nI\'m now integrating a sleek dark theme directly into `src/App.tsx` using Tailwind v4. I\'m focusing on a modern aesthetic with slate colors and deep green accents to highlight the encryption features. I\'m prioritizing clear explanations, such as the E2EE description of browser-side AES-GCM 256-bit encryption, which the server won\'t see keys for. The `index.css` is only importing Tailwind.\n\n\n**Implementing Share Feature**\n\nI\'ve just added a \"H\304\261zl\304\261 Payla\305\237\304\261m Linki\" feature, letting users create pre-filled links like `?room=X&key=Y` for easy sharing. Now, I\'m verifying the development environment. I need to complete the implementation of `src/App.tsx` and review imports, including lucide-react icons and `motion/react` animations.\n\n\n"
